    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Stories of a Stricken City, and a Grieving Land; Bravo, Mr. Giuliani!</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Larry Liebling letter praises Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's leadership in aftermath of terror attack on New York (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In reflecting on the early moments that have followed this enormous tragedy and challenge to our country, we can all be grateful for the leadership of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. He has stood in the breach and has been the voice of calm and reassurance, the voice against overreaction and the voice of strength.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In reflecting on the early moments that have followed this enormous tragedy and challenge to our country, we can all be grateful for the leadership of Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani. He has stood in the breach and has been the voice of calm and reassurance, the voice against overreaction and the voice of strength.</p>
        <p>Not only have New Yorkers been able to look to his stewardship but so, too, the entire country.</p>
        <p>In this day, when we have become so used to disappointment from our leaders, Mr. Giuliani has reflected the best part of our own nature in this trying time. Not only has he rallied the city to great feats of courage and kindness, but he has also soothed our fears. He has held back the chaos, quieted the tendency to lash out against the darkness and set the tone for healing.</p>
        <p>We can only hope that our national leadership guides us down the right path. Too often in the past, our leaders have taken advantage of America's good heart and led us down ugly byways. It is time to put away thoughts of political gain and live up to the principles that make this country a bastion of freedom and hope.</p>
        <p>LARRY LIEBLING  Bellmore, N.Y., Sept. 13, 2001</p>
      </block>
